      "The great deceiver gets deceived, and it is devastating. Jacob arrives in Haran, sees Rachel at a well, and falls so hard he single-handedly rolls away a stone that normally requires multiple shepherds. He agrees to work seven years for the right to marry her, and the text delivers one of the most romantic lines in Scripture: the years 'seemed to him but a few days because of the love he had for her.' Then comes the wedding night, the darkness, the veil — and morning reveals Leah in Rachel's place.\n\nJacob's outrage to Laban is almost comically ironic: 'Why have you deceived me?' The man who dressed in his brother's clothes and pretended to be someone else has now been handed the wrong bride under cover of night. Laban's reply is a surgical strike: 'It is not so done in our country, to give the younger before the firstborn.' The man who stole the firstborn's blessing has run headlong into a culture that enforces birth order. The symmetry is merciless.\n\nJacob agrees to work another seven years for Rachel, and within a week he has two wives, one beloved and one merely tolerated. The seeds of a deeply painful household are planted, and they will grow into a family defined by rivalry, jealousy, and the ache of being unloved.",
