    summary:
      "The birth of Israel's twelve tribes unfolds not as sacred history but as a brutal fertility competition between two desperate sisters. Leah, unloved but fertile, names each son as a prayer: Reuben ('see, a son!') because 'the Lord has looked upon my affliction'; Simeon because 'the Lord has heard that I am hated'; Levi because 'now this time my husband will be attached to me.' Each name is a wound dressed as gratitude. Meanwhile Rachel, beloved but barren, is consumed by jealousy and demands of Jacob, 'Give me children, or I shall die!'\n\nThe competition escalates into surrogacy warfare. Rachel offers her servant Bilhah; Leah counters with Zilpah. Children are born, named, and weaponized. Leah trades mandrakes — a fertility herb — for a night with her own husband, a transaction so bleak it defies commentary. Rachel gets the mandrakes; Leah gets Jacob. The scorekeeping is relentless.\n\nBy the time Rachel finally bears Joseph, the household includes twelve children by four different mothers, each child carrying a name that encodes their mother's pain, longing, or triumph. Israel is not born from a loving family; it is born from a family at war with itself.",
