    summary:
      "One of the strangest chapters in Genesis interrupts the Joseph story to tell us about the time Judah slept with his daughter-in-law — and she turned out to be more righteous than he was. Judah leaves his brothers, marries a Canaanite woman, and has three sons. The eldest, Er, marries Tamar but dies because he is 'wicked in the sight of the Lord.' Judah gives Tamar to his second son, Onan, to fulfill the levirate duty of producing an heir for his dead brother. Onan takes the conjugal benefits but deliberately avoids the reproductive responsibility, and God kills him too.\n\nJudah, now afraid that his third son Shelah will also die, sends Tamar back to her father's house with a promise he has no intention of keeping. Tamar waits. And waits. When it becomes clear that Judah is never going to honor his obligation, she takes matters into her own hands — disguising herself as a prostitute, positioning herself at a crossroads, and sleeping with Judah himself. She demands his seal, cord, and staff as collateral.\n\nWhen Tamar's pregnancy becomes visible, Judah orders her burned for prostitution. She produces his seal and staff: 'The man who owns these got me pregnant.' Judah's response is one of the most honest sentences in the Bible: 'She is more righteous than I.' The woman who posed as a prostitute is vindicated; the man who withheld justice is exposed.",
